name: 3-phenylprop-2-enyl cinnamate
Reason: The compound 3-phenylprop-2-enyl cinnamate contains multiple functional groups that influence its melting point: two phenyl groups, an ester group, two alkene groups, and an ether linkage. The base structure here can be considered as styrene, which has a melting point of -30°C. Each phenyl group can be estimated to add rigidity to the structure and can raise the melting point by approximately 20°C (in the absence of the alkene group). The ester linkage introduces polarity and the ability for additional dipole-dipole interactions, which can raise the melting point by approximately 50°C. The alkene groups slightly decrease the melting point due to their electron-rich nature and less effective van der Waals interactions, estimated at -5°C each. The ether linkage, while being an oxygen-containing group which can increase polarity and potential for hydrogen bonding, in this context is not expected to significantly influence the melting point due to its position and the surrounding non-polar groups, contributing about +5°C due to the additional atom and slight dipole character. Combining these effects on top of the base structure melting point yields the predicted value.
